# Vertical Slice Architecture

A feature is a **verb-based use case** (e.g., `create_order`, `get_user_detail`), not an entity bucket.

## Feature Layout

Features live under `src/features/<area>/<verb>/` with at most four files:

```
src/features/
  orders/
    create_order/
      router.py
      service.py
      schemas.py
    get_order_detail/
      router.py
      service.py
      schemas.py
  notifications/
    send_notification/
      service.py
      job.py
```

Area folders (`orders/`, `notifications/`) are **grouping prefixes only** — they carry no runtime behavior.

## Dependency Rules

| Layer | May depend on | Must NOT depend on |
|---|---|---|
| `features/**/router.py` | Its own service, `shared/api/`, `shared/kernel/` | Other features, orchestrators |
| `features/**/service.py` | `shared/kernel/`, `shared/infrastructure/` | Other features, `api/routes/` |
| `orchestrators/**/service.py` | Feature services, `shared/kernel/` | Other orchestrators |
| `shared/kernel/` | Nothing external | Features, orchestrators, infrastructure |

## Rules

- **New endpoint or job** → create a new verb folder. Never add a second endpoint to an existing verb.
- **Cross-domain workflow** → goes into `orchestrators/`, not into a feature.
- **Routers bind HTTP**, call ONE service method, return the result. No business logic in routers.
- **Services are instantiated per request** — no shared mutable state.

## Example: Wrong vs Right

```python
# WRONG — entity bucket with multiple verbs crammed in
# src/features/orders/service.py
class OrderService:
    async def create(self, ...): ...
    async def get_detail(self, ...): ...
    async def cancel(self, ...): ...

# RIGHT — one verb, one folder, one service
# src/features/orders/create_order/service.py
class CreateOrderService:
    async def execute(self, cmd: CreateOrderCommand) -> Order: ...
```
